---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import ProgressTimeline from "../../components/ProgressTimeline.astro";
import ProtoBiasDemo from "../../components/ProtoBiasDemo.tsx";

// Project milestones — each "done" node links to its own standalone report.
const progress = [
  {
    date: "8 Jun 2026",
    phase: "Experiment 1 · Report 1",
    title: "The bias follows the attribute, not the language",
    summary:
      "The first multilingual pipeline: 3,600 judgments from Qwen2.5-VL-7B across English, Chinese, Arabic, and Hindi, with the full domain × language and attribute breakdowns, confidence intervals, and caveats.",
    href: "/research/cross-lingual-protobias/report-1",
    status: "done",
  },
  {
    date: "21 Jun 2026",
    phase: "Experiment 2 · Report 2",
    title: "It replicates across models — and language is not flat after all",
    summary:
      "Scaled to two model families (Qwen2.5-VL-7B and InternVL3-8B) and seven languages, adding Russian, Bengali, and Greek across resource levels and scripts. An item-clustered mixed-effects analysis confirms the attribute effect (Wealth, Power) in both families; adding the lower-resource and distinct-script prompts surfaces a language effect the first four languages missed — Bengali and Greek elicit measurably more bias than English — and a back-translation check rules out translation quality as the cause.",
    status: "done",
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="Cross-lingual ProtoBias · Xiaochuan Li"
  description="An applied multilingual/multimodal stress test of semantic grounding versus language- and culture-specific prototype shortcuts."
  showProgress={true}
  toc={true}
>
  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Extension · applied stress test
    </div>
    <h1>Cross-lingual ProtoBias</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      Semantic grounding versus prototype shortcuts under language variation.
    </p>

    <p>
      Cross-lingual ProtoBias carries the framework's semantic-vs-shortcut question into multilingual,
      multimodal evaluation: does an MLLM judge track the meaning of an image–text pair, or lean on a
      language- and culture-specific prototype? Each prompt is shown with two images — one semantically
      correct but less prototypical, one more prototypical but wrong — so a judge that prefers the
      typical-but-wrong image is riding the shortcut, structurally the same failure certified in
      <a href="/research/sc-certification">Stable Is Not Grounded</a>. The cross-lingual turn holds the
      image pairs fixed and translates only the prompt: if the verdict moves with the language, the
      judge is importing expectations a language-independent meaning would not. It is an applied stress
      test of the central framework, not a separate thesis spine.
    </p>

    <h2>Roadmap</h2>
    <p>
      The project advances in dated milestones; each completed node opens its own standalone report.
    </p>
    <ProgressTimeline items={progress} accent="var(--accent-deep-purple)" />

    <h2>Latest progress</h2>
    <p>
      The most recent milestone — <strong>Report 2</strong> — scaled the probe to two model families
      (Qwen2.5-VL-7B and InternVL3-8B) and seven languages, adding Russian, Bengali, and Greek to span
      resource levels and scripts. Two results <strong>replicate across both families</strong>: the bias
      is <strong>attribute-specific</strong> (concentrated on Wealth and social status, near chance for
      Morality and Intellect), and — once lower-resource, distinct-script prompts are added — a
      <strong>language effect that the first four languages missed</strong> appears: Bengali and Greek
      elicit measurably more bias than English. A back-translation check rules out translation quality,
      and there is no attribute × language interaction, so the attribute <em>pattern</em> is
      language-invariant while the overall <em>level</em> is not. Report 1's "language barely moves it"
      now reads as a four-language artifact. Code and figures:
      <a href="https://github.com/xchuan-li/cross_lingual_protobias">cross_lingual_protobias →</a>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The interactive read below is the original <strong>four-language</strong> picture from Report 1 —
      the prototype bias swings sharply by attribute, and only mildly by language until the
      lower-resource prompts of Report 2 are added:
    </p>

    <ProtoBiasDemo client:visible />

    <h2>Research questions</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>RQ1:</strong> Is prototypicality bias consistent across languages when the semantic
        content of the prompt is held fixed?
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>RQ2:</strong> Are cross-lingual differences stronger in socially sensitive contexts
        such as wealth, intelligence, and profession than in neutral domains such as animals or
        objects?
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>AI relation</h2>
    <p>
      The project uses multimodal large language models as evaluators of image-text alignment. The
      key object of study is not only whether a model gets an item right, but what kind of signal its
      decision appears to ride on: semantic consistency, visual typicality, or a culturally specific
      prototype activated by the prompt language.
    </p>

    <h2>Data</h2>
    <p>
      The project uses the ProtoBias dataset, with prompts translated into multiple languages while
      keeping the image pairs fixed. This makes the translation itself an intervention on the
      linguistic presentation of the same underlying semantic task.
    </p>

    <h2>Literature</h2>
    <p class="!text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)] !mb-3">Source benchmark and the closest related work.</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Roy, Bhatia &amp; Eger. <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2601.04946">ProtoBias</a> — the source benchmark this project extends.</li>
      <li>Hausladen, Knott, Camerer &amp; Perona. <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2408.14435">Social Perception of Faces in a Vision-Language Model</a> (FAccT 2025) — bias concentrates unevenly across social-trait dimensions, paralleling our attribute-specific result.</li>
      <li>Al Sahili, Patras &amp; Purver. <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.14160">Breaking Language Barriers or Reinforcing Bias?</a> (IJCNLP-AACL 2025) — multilingual VLMs show stronger bias than English, largest in low-resource languages; the closest mirror of our language effect.</li>
      <li>Neplenbroek, Bisazza &amp; Fernández. <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2406.07243">MBBQ</a> (CoLM 2024) — non-English stereotypes exceed English even after controlling for culture; the text-only precedent, with a control parallel to our back-translation check.</li>
      <li>Friedrich et&nbsp;al. <a href="https://aclanthology.org/2025.acl-long.966/">Multilingual T2I Generation Magnifies Gender Stereotypes</a> (ACL 2025) — cross-lingual bias variation in image generation; a contrasting modality.</li>
    </ol>
  </article>
</Base>
